description: Python coding conventions for this workspace
alwaysApply: false
---
Follow PEP 8 guidelines as a default. The following rules take precedence.

## Import 

1. Don't use import statements inside functions, unless it actually needs to be there. Put imports at the top of the file. 
2. Use separate sections for stdlib modules, third-party modules and local modules. Sort each section alphabetically.

## Package preferences

1. Use `pathlib` for all path related operations, whenever possible.

## Syntax preferences
1. Use f-strings for string formatting whenever possible.
2. When calling functions, use keyword arguments whenever possible e.g. `foo(arg=value)`, not `foo(value)`.

## Type hints
1. Use type hints whenever possible.
2. Function arguments and return value should use a single type when possible. Try not to mix types.

## Docstrings and comments
1. Use docstrings and comments focusing on the "why" (as opposed to "what" or "how"). Readers of the code should be able to read docstrings or comments to get a high-level overview of why the code is organized the way it is i.e. which abstraction does a function achieve and why this is a good abstraction etc.

## Scripts
1. For scripts, arguments that users can *reasonably expect to modify* should be exposed as a command line argument, with suitable defaults. Don't use module level vars for specifying defaults in such cases.

## Logging
1. Use the `logging` module whenever possible instead of `print()`.
